		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Holland, Europe - June 2005<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(5.00)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=11045'>Patrick "Patrick M. S" Sullivan</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=11045&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> July 6, 2006</font><p align='justify'><blockquote><font class="bfont"> Note from me: Hey all, I’d been meaning to do this for sometime now. I wanted to move all my Tournament Reports from the Decipher and DGMA sites to Decktech and Gameplayersnetwork since they are easier to find here and I’m worried that Decipher’s two sites will go down eventually. I wouldn’t want to lose all these awesome memories. So here they are, archived, for your amusement. Feel free to give reviews with your thoughts and memories of the events or to simply let me know how you liked the read. <br />
<br />
Mr. Sullivan goes to Holland (and also goes The Netherlands)<br />
<br />
Friday, June 17th to Sunday, June 19th<br />
<br />
Pre-tourney Jank<br />
<br />
Although it may seem initially crazy to fly all the way to Holland to simply win Fan Dollars and a shot at winning either a free flight to GenCon or free hotel stay at a future Decipher event, the fact of the matter is that I had a ton of fan dollars to spend and a free trip to Holland seemed perfect. I had never been before and I knew a ton of people that would be there so it would be a great way to kick start my summer tournament season. <br />
<br />
With both a Premier Series Event and the European Continental Championships, I knew I had to bring a sturdy Standard format deck that could handle a variety of meta. So I packed up my Noble Leaders fellowship with a Gandalf condition removal splash and paired it up with a Forest Nazgul shadow that is largely helped with the 4x Well Travelled and 2x Anduril, Flame of the West to help set up 5 forests by the 1st or 2nd turn of play. This maximizes my Dark Approaches to their full –4 twilight cost bonus as well as making my Lost in the Woods +5 strength each. Once my fellowship sets up, I can actually handle 2 triple moves against a variety of shadows. I can bid one to go first, play Trollshaw Forest at site one, hopefully draw a Well Travelled or two to get out 4 other forests immediately, playing The Angle at site 2 and probably Old Forest Road at site 3. Then, if you have another Well-Travelled at site 3, you can dump Caras Galadhon and Woody End for 4 and 5 and you’re all set. I would then use Denethor to fetch Elendil and Narsil, doubling to 5, using Narsil to put either Neekerbreeker’s Bog or Cavern Entrance at 6 and triple move. Then in regroup phase, I ditch Narsil, fetch another one with Denethor and triple to site 9 using Noble Leaders, Devorin, Well Travelled and Lord knows what else. <br />
<br />
At least that’s how the deck works on paper. In theory, as we will see, it doesn’t always happen like it does in the fairy tales. Either my shadow kills much faster than I thought (at site 4 and 5 almost all the time) or my fellowship dies much faster than I thought it would (at site 7 most of the time). So, the deck did extremely well at the Gatineau, Quebec TOC and placed 4th in the last online PSQ losing only to a mirror match. So I figured it was worth bringing to Fortress Europe. <br />
<br />
<br />
Day Zero<br />
Thursday, June 16th, 2005<br />
<br />
So my sister kindly drives me to the airport the night before for my 6pm flight. She does a nice imitation of our mother who slams the brakes everytime she thinks she sees a parking spot. We were rollin’ laughing while trying to find a spot in the airport parking lot for 20 minutes. We get in and I get in line to check in. This little girl who is ugly as sin is in line in front of me and she’s playing with everyone’s luggage. Pulling cords, opening latches, you name it. The kid is completely out of control. The thought that she might be on my flight doesn’t even cross my mind. I get my ticket finally and am not assigned a window seat as I had requested because our plane got upgraded to a 747. Meaning more seats since the passenger manifold hasn’t changed from the smaller MD-11 aircraft we were supposed to take. The girl tells me to grab a window seat after takeoff. There should be one available. <br />
<br />
So I get on the plane and find my seat is beside some teenage boy who’s looking pretty nervous about being on a plane. He’s in the window seat and I’m supposed to be right beside him but I really really want his seat instead. So just from the envious way I was looking at his seat, he asks, “Oh, is this your seat?” and I quickly say “yes.” So he gets out of his own seat and I take it even though it’s not mine. The only drawback to this is that he’s even more nervous sitting in the aisle seat cuz he can’t see outside. So he’s rocking back and forth like a complete lunatic for the first 2 hours. <br />
<br />
Oh, I should mention that the first two hours and a half are spent on the ground in Montreal since there is a thunderstorm going on. And who sits right in front of me? That little ugly girl from the line. She’s whining like crazy to her mom who just keeps giving her more toys and stuff to keep her quiet. As soon as the plane finally takes off and levels out, the kid beside me bolts for another window seat and I stretch out on the 3 empty seats to claim them all for my own so I can sleep (remember, this flight leaves at 8pm but arrives at 7 am, so I gotta get some shuteye otherwise tomorrow will be a nightmare). The movie is Be Cool (sequel to Get Shorty), it’s pretty good and I quickly fall asleep afterwards. Waking up as we fly over Ireland, I grab my deck and give myself a deck check for lack of nothing else to do. It should be noted that deck checks should be done at home since if I were to be missing a card (like I did in Vegas), you can’t really do anything about it since you didn’t bring all your cards. Anyway, I pass the deck check and I make sure I don’t misspell any of the words to not get a game loss on Day Two of a PSE. Everything checks out fine. It’s at this point that the little girl has crawled under her seat and is swatting my feet and legs with her arms for some strange reason. Her mom is no where to be found and I’m like, “Is that a shark attacking me? I didn’t know there were sharks on airplanes.” And she responds to me in some language I can’t recognize. Some sort of cross between French and German which is think is Dutch but aren’t sure. The fact that she doesn’t understand me is kinda fun though so the next time she swats me I say, “I’m sending you to the Neverland Ranch if this keeps up.” Well, that didn’t work either so 4 more minutes of getting smacked around by this little devil and her mom comes back and tells her to stop (in English, mind you). Oops.<br />
<br />
So after almost 9 hours in the plane, I arrive in Amsterdam airport. Eric Minkes, level 4 DGMA judge, is putting me up in his Amsterdam apartment and is also picking me up at the airport but is nowhere to be seen. Luckily, I have his cell phone number so I try using one of these fancy computer phones in the airport and end up calling Australia by accident. I’m sure that’ll cost me a pretty penny. Anyway, I end up getting in touch with him and we hook up with Jurgen (I can never remember what this guy’s actual name was), a Dutch player who arrived by train and the three of us hit Burger King which I actually had for lunch the day before in Montreal. So I have the Big King trio and it tastes exactly the same as it does at home save for the Fanta orange soda which is an entirely different thing than Orange Crush. <br />
<br />
We then pick up Martin Hornachek from Bratslavia which is either in Slovakia or the Chech Republic. I can’t remember. Martin is Your_Fat_Daddy in the online game and is part of my guild, Patzachia, so it’s good to meet him finally in person. We then go to Eric’s apartment where I’m happy to see he has an Xbox with Halo and 4 controllers, as well as a great selection of DVDs including Ghost Dog (which Eric hasn’t even seen yet), Spirited Away and many other good titles. I see that I’m going to have to blow up an air mattress to sleep on but don’t have the energy right now cuz I’m wiped from the flight. So the four of us head into town in Eric’s Ford Focus. <br />
<br />
Martin has to break down his big Euro bills into smaller denominations so while he’s in the bank, I spot this cute girl chattin’ with two guys. I approach them and they turn out to be Irish so they direct me to a local pub, Slainte, where we end up going for club sandwiches and Strongbow. We then start shopping for books and I’m amazed that paperbacks cost more than 16 Euro each. Eric buys the Life is Beauitful DVD and I start falling asleep standing up so we head back and I take a nap. Eric was going to show us the Red Light District but we couldn’t find it. Probably a good thing. <br />
<br />
After the nap, we head out to see Batman Begins on IMAX which ends up being really good. Gotta go to the men’s room after the movie and right before you walk in, there’s this giant mirror wall beside the entrance. So on the way out, I thought I had to turn right, and I walk right into myself (the mirror), I stop, look up and say, ‘pardon me.’ After realizing what I had done, I felt pretty stupid and realized the jet lag was affecting me quite strongly.<br />
<br />
We then hit up a pizza joint and I order a Pizza Americana (with pepperoni), it turns out to be 10 times better than the pizza in Montreal which is always terrible wherever you go. We get back to the apartment and try out 4-player Halo. I don’t think any of these guys have played much since every map I completely wreck the whole lot of them. I start abusing the rocket launcher and sniper rifle just to have more fun but it doesn’t change the result and we stop playing. Someone was nice enough to blow up my air mattress when I was napping earlier so I quickly pass out for the night.<br />
<br />
Day One<br />
Friday, June 17th, 2005<br />
<br />
A bunch of Germans arrived late at night so when I get up and start walking around in my boxer briefs, I’m kinda surprised to see the living room full of new people that weren’t there the night before, including a girl. So I embarrassingly run back to the room and change. So we are now 6 people in Eric’s Ford Focus and I’m jammed in the back for the 30-minute car ride to Utrecht. But there is heavy traffic getting into town and it ends up almost taking an hour. We get there and I meet Jonas Skali for the first time who has chosen to play in the WARS PSE. I think they got 6 people in all for that one so I wished him the best of luck in making day two. <br />
<br />
The event is being held in some building on the 2nd floor. The entire first floor is a bar/café-type area where luckily tea/coffee/sandwiches are all really cheap. So I get a ham and cheese sandwich and a latte for something crazy like 3 euro. Can’t believe how inexpensive it was. The complete opposite of American conventions where everything costs an arm and a leg. I then take another couple lattes since I get a free earned bye in round one of the PSE and start talking to Frederic Lafont who I met in Vegas. Fred is from Lyon I think. I also meet this cool Irish guy who is playing Star Trek for the weekend. I think they got 8-10 people for their event that weekend (I believe it was a Continental Championship but I’m not sure). I tried watching a few games of Trek between rounds but it’s like watching paint dry. I choose instead to watch Skali and some other cool German poker-playing guy play WARS. Always a fun game to watch. <br />
<br />
Tania who is the head organizer over the weekend seems pretty nervous but I’m sure everything will go just fine. Soon round two is about to be called so I go upstairs with whatever’s left from my 3rd café latte and get ready to play. Around 60 players have shown up for the PSE Day one so I’m sure it won’t be easy with Kenneth Ellingsen, Martin Hechtberger, Bernd Reinhart and a few other great players in the running.<br />
<br />
Round One<br />
Bye<br />
1-0<br />
<br />
Round Two <br />
Opponent: David Van Der Sloot from Eindhoven (Dutch town liberated by the 506th Airborne if I’m not mistaken. The paratrooper Division featured in Band of Brothers)<br />
Deck: Forest Nazzies with huge Witch King / Gandalf – Saved from the Fire<br />
Good: David was a crazy nice guy as I quickly found all Dutch to be<br />
Bad: I’m making a ton of mistakes such as not paying roaming for Witch King at site 2, playing Saplings when I don’t have unbound companions to spot, and forgetting to make David exert with my Out of Sight and Shot. Grrrrr...<br />
Ugly: For some stupid reason, I decide to double to site 3 when David plays nothing at site 2. At site 3, he plays WitchKing (the new bad version), Pale-Blade and Witch-King’s Beast. This single minion kills Faramir, Denethor AND Aragorn leaving me with solo Boromir at the sanctuary. OUCH<br />
Result: FL Shadow Kill site 5<br />
1-1<br />
<br />
Well that smartened me up. Ken reminds me that once my fellowship sets up, Nazgul can barely touch it. I should single to site 3 and get the good stuff with Denethor before becoming aggressive. I’ll have to remember that.<br />
<br />
Round Three <br />
Opponent: Germany’s Peyman Satrapi, great guy who also plays poker and smokes cigars singing really annoying songs while playing J<br />
Deck: Enduring Enquea / Eowyn-Legolas<br />
Good: He forgets to heal at site 3 by using Dammed Gate Stream first with both Eowyn and Glorfindel exhausted. Yay!<br />
Bad: This match-up is crazy bad for both my fellowship and shadow<br />
Ugly: He gets Enquea out each site with Between nazgul and Prey and quickly adds 10 burdens in no time.<br />
Result: FL corruption site 5<br />
1-2 <br />
<br />
Oh boy, looks like I’m going to have to win all 4 of my next games to make Day Two. L<br />
<br />
Round Four <br />
Opponent: Gwen Engels<br />
Deck: Dworcs<br />
Good: Very nice guy to play against<br />
Bad: He doesn’t get BRC out at all this game which is essential against my Forest Nazgul<br />
Ugly: The entire game, he has a destroyer or two at each site and me with 8 threats all the time. <br />
Result: FW shadow kill site 5<br />
2-2<br />
<br />
3 more to go...<br />
<br />
Round Five <br />
Opponent: French player Nicolas Marcelli<br />
Deck: Dunland! (sweet) / Noble Leaders<br />
Good: Nice opponent once again<br />
Bad: This was such a ridiculously advantaged match up for me. <br />
Ugly: I double to site 3 and then triple move twice for the win!<br />
Result: FW site 9<br />
3-2<br />
<br />
It’s the fastest I’ve ever won a game at site 9 before. So I take Nicolas down for a coffee and we relax a bit before the next round.<br />
<br />
Round Six <br />
Opponent: Tomak (aka Spider777 online, winner of an online PSQ this year with Corsairs)<br />
Deck: Dwarf-Smeagol / Corsair<br />
Good: This was my toughest match so far. Tomah is a serious up and comer and this game and I had to make sure not to make any errors. <br />
Bad: He plays BRC twice on me to wipe out my conditions<br />
Ugly: Castamir is wounded once against 15 stength Elendil. I say I pass seeing that Castamir is 14 strength. I completely forget what ‘enduring’ means I guess and I lose the skirmish. Eric Minkes tells me it must be the jet lag. <br />
Result: FW site 9 after playing Well-Travelled to play Neekerbreeker Bog and then forgetting to heal my entire fellowship. OMG. Somebody shoot me<br />
4-2<br />
<br />
Only one more win to go and I’m in day two!<br />
<br />
Round Seven <br />
Opponent: Eventual winner of Sunday’s Continental Championship, Quentin de Varresses<br />
Deck: Same deck he used to win Sunday’s EC, Running Hobbits with Forest Nazgul<br />
Good: Really nice French player who always smiles<br />
Bad: We run out of tokens to fit on the 4 Sudden Fury’s which each have 8 or 9 tokens on them. So we decide to use dice. I play 3 or 4 Nazgul at a site and he has to remove tokens to avoid overwhelming and then adds tokens for losing skirmishes. The time it takes to find numbers on a ten-sided die 8 TIMES each skirmish (once per condition for adding strength, once per condition for losing skirmish) ends up making sites take 20 minutes each. I am unable to think of another solution for managing these stupid conditions and I know Quentin is going as fast as he can so I don’t want to tell him to speed up or anything. <br />
Ugly: He doubles to site 7 and I devastate his fellowship. However times runs out and I’m at site 6 so he gets a Timed Win. He didn’t stall me out and it wasn’t entirely his fault that we went to time since it was more the circumstances involved around Sudden Fury with tons of tokens, so I give him the Full Win and it gets him into Day Two. Yay!<br />
Result: TL site 7<br />
4-3<br />
<br />
It’s not a strong enough finish and nabs me 30th out of 60 players. I’m really frustrated about losing to time in that last game since I feel I would have been able to kill his fellowship by site 9 but I talk about it with Quentin and we realize there was nothing we could do at the time to make the game go faster. In retrospect, I suppose I should get a piece of paper and pen to quickly change numbers on Sudden Fury. But I was playing terrible all day long and didn’t really deserve to get into Day Two so I’ll just rehone my skills for the Continentals on Sunday. <br />
<br />
So it’s now getting late and we’re pretty hungry so Eric takes us to Macdonald’s where they have this McPita which I’m too scared to try. Jurgen orders a McCroket which is this weird sandwich with a deep-fried patty filled with ragout or something. It was bizarre. Eric tells me he hasn’t seen Sin City yet and judging by his DVD collection, we have similar tastes in film. I really liked Sin City and have already seen it twice but would totally be willing to see it again. So we go to the movie theatre for the 2nd night in a row and see Sin City. Eric loved it (as predicted) and Martin hated it (but he also hated Kill Bill so no surprise that he wouldn’t like Sin City). To get Martin to come, I had to promise him I’d help him build his Day Two PSE deck for Saturday but as soon as I got home, I fell fast asleep again. <br />
<br />
Day Two<br />
Saturday, June 18th <br />
<br />
I’m having the hardest time getting out of ‘bed’ because my internal time clock is 6 hours back. So when Eric is clapping his hands at 8 in the morning to get me out of bed, it’s 2 in the morning my time so I ain’t budgin’. Luckily, Eric is quite witty and makes me a single cup of coffee each morning and just says the word, ‘coffee.’ And I spring out of the half-deflated air mattress for that sweet java nectar of the gods. <br />
<br />
We then head out to the event hall in Utrecht and the PSE day two starts right away. There’s no match-ups worth watching at this point so I check out the side events. There is a reflections draft that I’m thinking of playing in but thankfully a contructed standard tournament gets thrown together and I sign up for that. It’s a 3-round 8 player tournament which is just perfect because a poker game is being organized and I want in on that sweet action later.<br />
<br />
Round One<br />
Opponent: Italy’s Daniele Farina<br />
Deck: Roaming Sauron / Merry-Rohan<br />
Good: Daniele has this silly goofy smile the entire game which keeps the match friendly <br />
Bad: In what will quickly turn into a recurring joke between Kenneth and I, the Italian friends of Daniele start to continuously coach him in Italian. It’s not until one of them looks at my hand and then speaks to Daniele in Italien that I lose it. I turn to the guy and say, “dude, you can’t talk to him and especially not in Italian after you’ve seen my hand! I mean, Christ, it’s ridiculous!”  LOL, I love when I go on tilt. If I saw myself on a camera afterwards, I think I’d be pretty embarrassed. <br />
Ugly: He gets out perfect (and I mean PERFECT) roaming sauron bombs at sites 3, 4 and 5. Completely wrecking my fellowship. I’m down to support splash companions only a and I stupidly lose Devorin at site 7 or 8 for no reason instead of taking wounds on Elendil or something. Kenneth who was watching says it’s the worst he’s seen someone play in a while. I’m a bad panda L<br />
Result: FW site 9. I barely survive. <br />
1-0<br />
<br />
Round Two<br />
Opponent: Primiano Cacetta (I know I butchered the spelling of this one)<br />
Deck: Mirror match but with Radagast splashed<br />
Good: Primiano was this really nice quiet guy who concentrates a lot on his game. <br />
Bad: He plays Buckland at site 4 and forgets to use it or get it back with Nelya. Kenneth laughs.<br />
Ugly: He plays 3 Lost in the Woods at site 7 right after I used Grown Suddenly Tall at site 6. DANG!<br />
Result: FL shadow kill site 7<br />
1-1<br />
<br />
no winning this tournament now. I blame that last loss on the Futurama Brain Slug I was wearing on my head. The German couple staying with us have this fluffy pink octopus that I wore as a hat and I think it impeded my thinking. <br />
<br />
Round Three<br />
Opponent: One of the Germans staying with us at Eric’s place, Christien Pfeiffer<br />
Deck: Sauron site control swarm / Dwarf-Smeagol<br />
Good: Christien is a crazy polite guy who barely speaks English making communication a fun challenge<br />
Bad: His shadow gets scary real fast once he gets 2 or 3 sites<br />
Ugly: Elendil is like the Canadian liberator of German-controlled Dutch sites. <br />
Result: TW site 8<br />
2-1<br />
<br />
I come in 3rd I think and now it’s time for poker since that cool German WARS player is done with his Day Two. I forgot what his name was but he was a crazy cool guy who looks a lot like Mathieu Brochu. So we have 6 or 7 people ready for a single-table Texas Hold ‘Em tournament with payout to top 3. It’s only 5 Euro so I decide to sign up. Other players are Vasco S, Andreas Petz, Peyman, Martin Hornachek and the guy who organized it who looks like Brochu. We’re quickly down to 4 players and I go all in with AQs and find myself up against QQ. Oops. I finish 4th. One away from the money. At least I lost to a good hand.<br />
<br />
After the poker, I head on upstairs to watch Ken Ellingsen playing in the semi-finals. I watch as he plays a Grown Suddenly Tall and then forgets to discarded his loaded Noble Leaders. Eric and I exchange glances and look to see if his opponent notices. He doesn’t and I chuckle. Ken goes on to the finals and I get ring-side seats for the Ken vs Bernd game. After 1-1, Ken has to think about how to handle the 3rd game for the win. Ken is playing Noble Leaders with Forest Nazguls against Bernd’s Forest Nazguls with Dwarf-Smeagol. Although I think afterwards that Ken should bid low, he bids high to go second forcing Bernd (who also bid high) to hit Neekerbreeker’s Bog repeatedly which stops him from being able to use BRC almost immediately. Ken has Bernd’s entire fellowship killed and then singles into site 7 and Bernd plays 5 Nazgul when was also capable of playing 6. Ken’s fellowship succumbs and Bernd is named PSE champion. <br />
<br />
This time, the tournament ends much later than the night before but you wouldn’t notice it from looking outside since there is light until almost 11pm because Holland is so far north. So we hit up MacDonald’s one last time and then back to the apartment. We watch Ghost Dog on DVD then to bed.<br />
<br />
Day Three<br />
Sunday, June 19th<br />
<br />
Once again, a nice cup of coffee wakes me up. I had incredible trouble falling asleep the night before and am especially wrecked this morning. We head over to Utrecht for Day Two of the Continentals. The original plan is that top 4 will play off in single-elimination at the end of 6 rounds but this wisely gets switched to top 8 half way through the tournament on the suggestion of one Andreas Petz. I’ve decided to keep the same deck since I’m playing better with it now. <br />
<br />
Round One<br />
Opponent: My Essen teammate, Kenneth Ellingsen! Players laugh when this pairing is announced. It’s even funnier when he’s paired up against our third teammate, Martin Hechtberger next round. <br />
Deck: Corsair Initiative / Dwarf-Smeagol<br />
Good: This was the most original Corsair built I’ve ever seen. Did you know that you play Castamirs without throwing in a single Raider Halberd into your deck? Apparantly, it’s pretty good.<br />
Bad: He’s playing Baruk Khazad x4 with Ring of Guiles and this proves to be devastating against my Forest Nazgul<br />
Ugly: He Fierce in Despairs away Elendil with Narsil at site 4. OUCH.<br />
Result: FL Shadow Kill site 7. Ken is completely decked and manages to play 4 pirates on my 3 companions and he has Wind that Sped Ships in hand. It’s over!<br />
0-1<br />
<br />
Round Two<br />
Opponent: Johan Maes from Belgium. This guy looks just like Cameron from Ferris Bueller’s Day Off.<br />
Deck: Evil Men Archery! With Noble Leaders<br />
Good: Real nice guy with an original shadow for once.<br />
Bad: He hits me with Anduin Banks at site 2 but fails to draw a Travelled Leader before site 4 so he can’t get it back. Whew<br />
Ugly: I play... NINE Nazgul at site 4 versus his 6 companions. I have never played so many in my life. I can’t believe what a huge kill this is going to be. Meanwhile my fellowship is moving to Neekerbreeker each site and is staying perfectly heathly against his archery shadow. So I say, “sorry” after playing nine nazgul and he says, “no big deal. I got to do what I came here to do.” I say, “What’s that?” He answers, “To play you.” I blush and buy him a cola J<br />
Result: FW shadow kill site 4<br />
1-1<br />
<br />
Round Three<br />
Opponent: Michel Spliet from Holland.<br />
Deck: Lurker Swarm / Dwarf-Gandalf<br />
Good: Real nice guy who always smiles and looks like one of the Hansen brothers.<br />
Bad: I go first and get to play ALL 8 of the first 8 sites versus his underground-dependant shadow.<br />
Ugly: I am at site 8 and am about to single into site 9. I have 5 companions on the table and he has 3 Demoralized on his support area. In my support area, I have Citadel of the Stars, Garrison of Osgiliath and Noble Leaders fully-loaded. In my hand I have Gandalf and Grown Suddenly Tall. I decide it’s better to keep my conditions and not give out 10 twilight for Gandalf with Grown Suddenly Tall since he probably won’t even add that much with his 3 Demoralized. So I single move giving a low amount of twilight. He plays Cavern Entrance so all my conditions are useless so I start to regret my decision, then he proceeds to exert my guys enough to add 27 pool into the twilight pool and play a huge swarm. I should have played Gandalf. I should also not have discarded 3 companions during the game just so I could stay at 5 (I even discarded Garrison of Gondor against a swarm deck!). Ken once again makes fun of me after the game.<br />
Result: FL shadow kill site 9<br />
1-2<br />
<br />
Well, there’s no way to make top 8 now but I try to salvage whatever rating I have left by attempting to win the rest of my games<br />
<br />
Round Four<br />
Opponent:  Joorst Mundi<br />
Deck: Dwarf-Gandalf / Southron Archery<br />
Good: Another nice opponent. <br />
Bad: I play 4 Nazgul at site 4 against 3 companions<br />
Ugly: 30 strength on Gimli<br />
Result: FW shadow kill site 4<br />
2-2<br />
 <br />
Round Five<br />
Opponent: Peyman, the German from yesterday who played Enduring Enquea<br />
Deck:weird Morc build with burden enquea / Elven Telepathy<br />
Good: it’s the cigar smokin’ poker guy!<br />
Bad: I discard Faramir’s Bow and Garrison of Gondor thinking he’s still playing Burden Enquea but both of these cards would have helped against Morcs L As soon as I discard Garrison, Ken groans and I realize I’ve made a bad mistake.<br />
Ugly: This game was going fine until the very end. I’m at site 8 and he’s at site 6. I have 8 nazgul in hand but I can’t kill his fellowship even if he doubles. There is about 2 minutes left on the clock and it’s his fellowship. He singles to site 7 and I think about which Nazgul to discard. I don’t feel I need to cycle because I thought I had no Fellowship left to draw in my deck. In the end I had two Saplings which would have helped enormously at site 9. Anyway I’m thinking about which Nazgul to discard and 5 seconds into it he says, “Don’t do this stall thing.” But he says it in a very accusatory way like he really suspected me of stalling him out when it’s his fault that there’s only a couple minutes left cuz he played so slow all game long. I tell him that I’ve never stalled in my life in this game and aren’t about to now. So I tell him how we’re now in the regroup phase since I haven’t played any Shadow in the interests of saving time. I discard a card and I think he moves again. Anyway, I still don’t play anything and I reconcile. At this point, I’m really incensed that he accuses ME of stalling when it’s the Germans who above and beyond any other player group are known for stalling out their opponents. I think my face must have been pretty red. I single into site 9 and win against just a little opposition. <br />
Result: FW site 9. He thanks me after the game for not stalling and forcing a timed win. I say ‘yeah, yeah, I’ll see you at the poker table.”<br />
3-2<br />
<br />
Round Six<br />
Opponent: Holland’s gem, Johan Bakker<br />
Deck: Uruk Resistance / Gandalf weird fellowship<br />
Good: This was such an awesome opponent. It’s exactly what I needed after my last match. We just laughed non-stop the entire match. All smiles and jokes for 30-45 minutes. Awesome.<br />
Bad: I triple to site nine against almost nothing.<br />
Ugly: Nothing was ugly in this game. It was the single most relaxing game I had all weekend. Johan rocks J<br />
Result: FW site 9<br />
4-2<br />
<br />
So with the crappy SOS I have, I can’t get into top 8 and finish 11th out of the 60 that are playing. Not too bad. I played much better today I think. While top 8 start getting together, I go downstairs with the same poker group and try one more tournament. I lose most of my money to Peyman and I feel much better playing poker with him than LOTR. I actually am feeling a little silly at this point about getting so upset about the stalling thing. I’m glad I decided to play poker with this cool group of Germans. Anyway, I end up against Vasco in a hand and go all-in pre-flop with KQo and he calls with 9Jo. Of course, a 9 is flopped and I lose everything. I run up to tell Ken about Vasco’s loose call and we have a good laugh. <br />
<br />
I then sit next to Ken to watch him play Quentin in the finals and it’s a real amazing match to watch. I spoke to both players before the match and both were 100% sure they were going to win. Quentin was the best cuz he didn’t care about winning at that point, he was ecstatic about making it to finals. <br />
<br />
Anyway, Ken got a bad draw and couldn’t get any of his Wind that Sped Ships when he needed them at the beginning of the game. Quentin made this insanely gutsy double move to 8 which really paid off since he could not have survived the double to nine. It was really impressive. Quentin lost companions at site 8 and regretted the move but after analyzing the game, we saw it was the right thing to do. Ken misplayed a Well Travelled at the beginning at site 3 and only played ONE site instead of two. The lack of the extra forest ended up making a huge difference when Quentin moved to site 3. Ken could have played an extra Nazgul. Oh well, it’s been a long weekend.<br />
<br />
So Tania and Eric give out prizes and then we pack things up and head back to Amsterdam. Jurgen suggests going to a nicer place than MacDonald’s and we go to some place where we can get ribs. They are certainly no Baton Rouge-type ribs but they hit the spot. We then head back to the apartment and I decide to sleep on the couch since I can’t seem to fall asleep on that air mattress. I put in The Last Samurai and fall asleep when Tom starts getting beaten up with a wooden stick. <br />
<br />
Day Four<br />
Monday, June 20th<br />
<br />
Once again, I just can’t seem to get out of bed. But I have to eventually, so I hop in the shower and we head to the airport. We get Martin to his flight, Jurgen to his train and I take Eric out for breakfast to thank him for his great hospitality. And what a breakfast it was! Eggs sunny-side up, bacon, croissants, baguettes, crumpets, café latte, freshly squeezed orange juice. I do believe it was the best meal I had all weekend. We had 3 or 4 hours to kill until my flight and Eric was nice enough to keep me company. So we talked a lot and he brought this really fun hot-air balloon racing board game which was so simple yet so strategic. I had so much fun that he gave me the game to bring back J <br />
<br />
I thank Eric and hope to see him in Essen and get on the plane. This time the plane is totally packed and I’m sitting beside some old talkative woman. I just bought a book with my last 20 Euro on the fall of Berlin at the end of WWII and she sees the book and keeps telling me what a bad time it was back them and how monstrous the Red Army was to German civilians. I jokingly say, “hey! Don’t ruin the book! I haven’t read it yet!” but she doesn’t find it funny at all. Oh well. At least she stops talking to me. <br />
<br />
The movie is Phantom of the Opera and it starts off real good and then quickly goes into Snoozeville, U.S.A. I get back into Montreal and think I see my ex-girlfriend working as a customs officer in the line I quickly change lines in case she bears any ill will and decides to give me a hard time. For once, customs doesn’t give me trouble and I get home and tear apart my flooding Noble Leader fellowship with hopes of never seeing it again. Dwarves are definitely where it’s at. <br />
<br />
All in all, it was an amazing trip. Really high competition so I wasn’t disappointed on that front. I was crazy impressed with the Dutch and their awesome hospitality. I look forward to returning to Amsterdam in the future.<br />
<br />
Props:<br />
·	David van der Sloot for destroying me in round two of the PSE and putting me right in my place. Especially after the judge said to you after calling out our pairing, “well, at least you’ll get a good SOS.” I think that guy jinxed me<br />
·	Kenneth Ellingsen for all the laughs and poker advice. It was great watching you play and hanging out<br />
·	Quentin for winning the EC and being a total Cinderella Story. Couldn’t happen to a nicer guy. Can’t wait to see you at Worlds. You better come!<br />
·	Tomak from Krakow for introducing himself and for being such a great player. Can’t wait to see more of you online and in the game. <br />
·	Fred Lafont for the great advice and for sharing lots of laughs<br />
·	Gregory for walking into a whore bar thinking it was a regular bar and throwing a woman off your lap when she sat down. That was the best story I’ve heard in a while.<br />
·	Johan Maes for getting to play me and telling me that’s the reason he came. You made me turn all red J<br />
·	Michel Spliet for giving the Dutch a good name with your great attitude. Thanks for destroying me at site 9 when I was 100% I was going to win J. At least I know how to play against Lurker Swarm now.<br />
·	Johan Bakker for being my favourite opponent of the weekend and for picking me up when I most needed it. <br />
·	Vasco for having a big chip stack and for being Vasco. Hurry up and get to Montreal!<br />
·	Andreas Petz for getting them to make a top 8<br />
·	Tania for all the chocolate are for running a really smooth E.C. Great volunteer!<br />
·	Tristan Marsman for doing so well and having a great sense of humour<br />
·	Eugenie and Miranda for being the two best female players in the world. <br />
·	Martin Hechtberger for the hugs and laughs. I wish you lived closer L<br />
·	Martin Hornacek for the laughs and for not getting mad that I’ve probably misspelled his name non-stop in this report as well as his home city (Bratslavia?) as well as forgetting which country he’s from (I’m pretty sure it was Slovakia). Oh man.. I’m so bad.<br />
·	Jurgen for all the same stuff and again for being a nice guy even though he’s crazy annoying most of the time. I think his name is actually spelled Jeroen actually but I’m not sure.<br />
·	Ken’s balding Norwegian friend who’s name I can’t remember but was all smiles all the time. Sorry we couldn’t find room for you at the poker table.<br />
·	That German guy that organized the whole poker thing and looks like Mathieu Brochu. You were one of my favourite guys out there and I can’t for the life of me remember what your name was. I totally suck. I think his name was Angelo Consoli now that I actually think about it but I’m really not sure. <br />
·	That guy who I played a pick-up game with who played morcs and his brother. You guys were crazy nice. <br />
·	All the volunteers that helped run events. <br />
·	That big Lukas guy who gave me an apple on the last day. <br />
·	The beautiful girl that worked the café/bar downstairs on Saturday. OMG was she ever cute.<br />
<br />
Massive Props<br />
·	Eric Minkes for opening up his home to me and being such an incredible host and ambassador both for Holland and for the game. He judged perfectly and justly and is the best Level 4 Judge I have ever seen since Enrique. I really hope that this summer’s judging will be similar. It certainly is reason enough to come to World Cup Essen. Anyway, thanks so much for everything. It’s cool to have so much in common with someone who lives so far away.<br />
<br />
Slops<br />
·	Jeroen and Martin for not even giving Ghost Dog a chance yet making fun of it non-stop while Eric and I are trying to watch it. It’s like trying to watch a movie with toddlers in the room but worse.<br />
·	Peyman for blindly accusing non-Germans of stalling. Not everyone plays the game the same way you guys do. <br />
